@@WWIZARD@@W

@@WHistory@@W
  The Wizard tradition claims the oldest lineage of any remort path: the
  Axiomatic Schools, founded when the first mortal arcanists decided that
  magic was not merely power but a discipline subject to formal proof. They
  built towers, wrote theorems, and insisted every spell effect could be
  defined, bounded, and perfected. The most rigorous of their successors
  became what the Schools called Artificers of Sequence -- practitioners
  who had reduced combat casting to a precise language of timing, window,
  and controlled output. When the formal title fell from use the common name
  that survived was Wizard: not a grand title but a technical one, meaning
  someone who has made the formless precise. A Mage who returns through the
  mortal path to study theory rather than raw power earns it honestly.

Wizards are precision arcanists: patient theoreticians who break combat into
angles, timing windows, and controlled spell sequencing. If Sorcerers are
wildfire, Wizards are the scalpel.

